  1. Use rename() to rename the columns and make them easier to use. The new column names should be:
  • country
  • commname
  • ASFIS_sciname
  • ASFIS_spcode
  • ISSCAAP_spgroup
  • ISSCAAP_spgroupname
  • FAO_area
  • unit
fisheries2 <- fisheries %>% 
  dplyr::rename(country = "Country",
                comname = "Common name",
                ASFIS_sciname = "ASFIS species name",
                ASFIS_spcode = "ASFIS species#",
                ISSCAAP_spgroup = "ISSCAAP group#",
                ISSCAAP_spgroupname = "ISSCAAP taxonomic group",
                FAO_area = "FAO major fishing area",
                unit = "Measure")

  1. Are these data tidy? Why or why not, and, how do you know? Use the appropriate pivot function to tidy the data. Remove the NAs. Put the tidy data frame into a new object fisheries_tidy.
    Data isnt tidy, the year is a column when it should be a variable
fisheries_tidy <- fisheries2 %>%  
  pivot_longer("1950":"2012",
              names_to = "year",
              values_to = "catch",
              values_drop_na = TRUE)

  filter(ISSCAAP_spgroupname == "Miscellaneous coastal fishes") %>%
  as.data.frame()

  1. Use the data to do at least one exploratory analysis of your choice. What can you learn? What are the top five of coastal fish caught in 2010?
coastal_fish %>% 
  filter(year == "2010") %>%
  group_by(ASFIS_sciname) %>% 
  summarize(top_coastal_fish = sum(catch, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(top_coastal_fish)) %>% 
  top_n(5)
